Bezanson/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false}],"milestone":null,"comments":21,"created_at":"2018-08-03T06:50:26Z","updated_at":"2024-10-10T17:17:10Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"NONE","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"The following MWE demonstrates a bug of mine: line 14 assume any exception has a field .msg .  This throws an exception, but in the presence of a return statement in the finally block, the exception is not propagated, and this was hard to track down.

I am of the opinion that, to help code development, an exception arising in a catch statement should be thrown, bypassing finally.  This will leave files unclosed, but help correcting the catch statement. Or the warning should be in big font in the manual!

```
function bungle(c)
    out = 0
    try
        @printf "\n\n\n\Bungling away\n"
        out = 1
        if c == 1
            @assert false @sprintf "We have a main %s undervolt" "B"
        elseif c==2
            a = sqrt(-1.)
        end
    catch ex
        out = 2
        @printf "catch block\n"
        @printf "Houston we have a problem: %s\n" ex.msg
    finally
        @printf "Shutting down.\n"
        return out
    end
end 
@show bungle(0)
@show bungle(1)
@show bungle(2)
```
